WEBVTT

00:03.710 --> 00:04.960
Meredith: When I was little,
I once asked my mother,

00:04.960 --> 00:07.880
"How do you tell
people such bad news?"

00:07.880 --> 00:10.500
"You tell them the truth,"
she said,

00:10.500 --> 00:12.920
"but you tell them
the best version of the truth

00:12.920 --> 00:15.540
you can come up with."

00:15.540 --> 00:17.880
My mother also never told me
I had a little sister.

00:17.880 --> 00:21.460
So, grain of salt.

00:21.460 --> 00:23.580
What are you doing up?
♪ Tiptoe past the graveyard ♪

00:23.580 --> 00:25.290
[ Sighs ] Couldn't sleep.
♪ On our best behavior ♪

00:25.290 --> 00:27.460
Neither could Ellis.
She wants some milk.

00:27.460 --> 00:29.420
Are Owen and Amelia
falling in love,

00:29.420 --> 00:31.420
or are they just falling
back into bed?

00:31.420 --> 00:33.620
That's what's keeping
you up at night?

00:33.620 --> 00:35.670
Not Jackson's
disappearing act?

00:35.670 --> 00:37.580
Jackson sent me a picture
of a tree.

00:37.580 --> 00:40.210
A picture of a tree?
Why?

00:40.210 --> 00:41.540
Look, what I'm saying is,

00:41.540 --> 00:43.380
if there's something
that Amelia can't see coming

00:43.380 --> 00:46.210
that's gonna pop out
and ruin everything,

00:46.210 --> 00:47.670
she should know
about it, right?

00:47.670 --> 00:50.710
Like you didn't see
the Jackson thing coming?

00:50.710 --> 00:52.620
No. Jackson's coming back.

00:52.620 --> 00:54.000
Is that what he said?

00:54.000 --> 00:55.330
♪ We've got all the time
in the world to kill ♪

00:55.330 --> 00:56.790
[ Sighs ]
The tree.

00:56.790 --> 00:57.960
What does a tree
have to do --

00:57.960 --> 00:59.460
And what if there
is something coming

00:59.460 --> 01:03.620
for Owen and Amelia
and there's no undoing it?

01:03.620 --> 01:05.620
Like, there's no picture
of a tree

01:05.620 --> 01:07.000
that could begin
to undo it?

01:07.000 --> 01:08.790
Do you need a sedative?

01:08.790 --> 01:10.670
Ellis: Mama.

01:10.670 --> 01:14.580
♪♪

01:14.580 --> 01:15.790
Go back to bed.

01:15.790 --> 01:17.460
Owen and Amelia are fine.

01:18.710 --> 01:21.040
I am not being ridiculous.
You are being ridiculous.

01:21.040 --> 01:22.620
God, you are such a hag!
[ Toys clatter ]

01:22.620 --> 01:24.170
[ Whispering ] Hey, hey, hey,
I just got Leo back down,

01:24.170 --> 01:25.790
so could we bring the volume
down, please?

01:25.790 --> 01:27.710
[ Whispering ]
We ha--
[ Toy squeaks ]

01:27.710 --> 01:29.170
We had one rule --
you do not do drugs.

01:29.170 --> 01:30.670
[ Whispering ] Well, great,
'cause I didn't do any drugs.

01:30.670 --> 01:32.290
Oh, you walked through
that door high as a kite,

01:32.290 --> 01:33.330
and if you think
that I can't --

01:33.330 --> 01:34.670
[ Door slams ]

01:34.670 --> 01:36.170
Sorry, Leo.

01:36.170 --> 01:37.380
♪ I'm digging in my hooks,
my pages on the floor ♪

01:37.380 --> 01:38.710
[ Sighs ]
Listen, she had a slip.

01:38.710 --> 01:40.000
I'm not sure shaming
her about it --

01:40.000 --> 01:41.710
I'm not shaming her
about a slip.

01:41.710 --> 01:42.920
I can handle a slip.

01:42.920 --> 01:44.670
What I will not
abide is for her

01:44.670 --> 01:46.830
to stand here
in my house --
My house.

01:46.830 --> 01:48.880
In your house
and lie right to my face.

01:48.880 --> 01:49.960
That is not okay.

01:49.960 --> 01:51.620
That is unacceptable,

01:51.620 --> 01:53.420
and I would think that I would
get a little backup from you.

01:53.420 --> 01:56.210
I backed you up.
You said, "Hey."

01:56.210 --> 01:57.540
Well, what do
you want to do?

01:57.540 --> 01:58.830
Well, I can't do
what I want to do,

01:58.830 --> 02:00.170
or we'd have to
hide her body.

02:00.170 --> 02:01.710
God, this is how
my mom must have felt.

02:01.710 --> 02:03.000
Let's go to bed.

02:03.000 --> 02:04.170
We'll think more clearly
about this in the morning.

02:04.170 --> 02:06.080
-[ Sighs ]
-Okay? Come on.

02:06.080 --> 02:07.750
Betty: Hag.
[ Normal voice ]
You know what?

02:07.750 --> 02:10.830
If you are gonna call me names,
call me names to my face!

02:10.830 --> 02:12.380
[ Leo crying ]

02:12.380 --> 02:13.620
Great.

02:13.620 --> 02:14.830
[ Sighs ]

02:14.830 --> 02:17.540
♪ Fill it up, fill it up ♪

02:17.540 --> 02:19.040
Okay, you're not here
right now, and, trust me,

02:19.040 --> 02:21.330
you really want to be.

02:21.330 --> 02:23.620
Yeah, well, I'm sorry.
My mind won't shut off.

02:23.620 --> 02:26.880
Mm. And something else
won't turn on.
[ Sighs ]

02:26.880 --> 02:28.670
Why did I take
this stupid job?

02:28.670 --> 02:29.880
Because you'll be
awesome at it.

02:29.880 --> 02:31.620
No, no, no, no.
I'm an awesome surgeon.

02:31.620 --> 02:33.120
I suck at this.

02:33.120 --> 02:34.830
And all anyone does
is ask for stuff.

02:34.830 --> 02:39.290
[ Sighing ]

02:39.290 --> 02:41.170
So, Bailey and I
are finally

02:41.170 --> 02:43.420
on the same page with
my fellowship.

02:43.420 --> 02:46.330
I'm gonna pitch that
we get an INUMAC MRI.

02:46.330 --> 02:47.880
Wait.

02:47.880 --> 02:49.960
You want an INUMAC MRI?

02:49.960 --> 02:51.670
Mm-hmm.
Everyone can use it.

02:51.670 --> 02:53.380
It'll pay for
itself eventually.

02:53.380 --> 02:54.580
[ Pager beeping, vibrating ]

02:54.580 --> 02:55.620
Mmm.

02:55.620 --> 02:57.670
Are you hitting me up
for money

02:57.670 --> 02:58.920
with your hand on my,
uh...

02:58.920 --> 03:01.290
What? Wait. Wait. No!
What? No!

03:01.290 --> 03:02.960
Alex, my hand was already
there from before.

03:02.960 --> 03:04.620
What -- No.

03:04.620 --> 03:06.880
Alex, you are the one who
wanted to talk about work.

03:06.880 --> 03:08.460
Where are you going?

03:08.460 --> 03:11.830
You made me feel dirty,
real dirty.
[ Laughs ] Oh, my --

03:11.830 --> 03:13.620
I wish I could
make you feel dirty.

03:13.620 --> 03:15.460
Oh, that's nice.
That's real nice.

03:15.460 --> 03:18.670
Alex, couldn't you just --
Oh, my -- Where --

03:18.670 --> 03:20.620
Come back to bed!

03:20.620 --> 03:21.670
[ Scoffs ]
[ Door slams ]

03:21.670 --> 03:23.790
[ Whimpers ]

03:27.540 --> 03:29.420
[ Indistinct conversations ]

03:29.420 --> 03:30.830
Hey, Chief, um,

03:30.830 --> 03:34.000
I just saw the funding for my
prosthetics project is frozen?

03:34.000 --> 03:35.960
Mm, temporarily.
Budget issues.

03:35.960 --> 03:37.420
Oh, man.

03:37.420 --> 03:38.710
We're gonna take that out
on little kids, though?

03:38.710 --> 03:40.540
Yes, and I know it's unfair,
so save it.

03:40.540 --> 03:42.500
[ Sighs ]

03:42.500 --> 03:44.080
Whoa.

03:44.080 --> 03:45.120
Morning, Dr. Grey.

03:45.120 --> 03:46.880
Good morning, Dr. Lincoln.

03:46.880 --> 03:49.210
Who's up, Helm?
A Mr. Saether.

03:49.210 --> 03:52.540
He's here for his --
Whoa.

03:52.540 --> 03:54.380
Uh, new makeup?

03:54.380 --> 03:56.210
Is there something
wrong with it?

03:56.210 --> 03:57.290
-No.
-No.

03:59.210 --> 04:03.380
[ Conversing in Italian ]

04:06.080 --> 04:08.040
Did Papa die?
No. Andrea!

04:08.040 --> 04:09.420
Why would you say that?

04:09.420 --> 04:11.580
[ Scoffs ]
You know why.

04:11.580 --> 04:13.750
Look, just don't let him drag
you into his crazy --

04:13.750 --> 04:14.960
I know, but --

04:14.960 --> 04:16.000
Wow.
Hi.

04:17.790 --> 04:18.960
Do you need something?

04:18.960 --> 04:20.460
Uh, no, nothing. Sorry.

04:20.460 --> 04:23.920
I just -- You look really, um --
You look very...uh --

04:23.920 --> 04:25.750
Capable.
Capable today.

04:25.750 --> 04:28.040
Thank you.
Uh...hi.

04:28.040 --> 04:33.830
♪♪

04:33.830 --> 04:39.460
♪♪

04:39.460 --> 04:42.080
[ Sighs ] What?

04:42.080 --> 04:43.880
I don't want to leave town

04:43.880 --> 04:47.040
when you're about to make
a great big fool of yourself

04:47.040 --> 04:48.880
over your lady boss.

04:48.880 --> 04:52.120
Oh, shut up.
I'm not --

04:52.120 --> 04:54.170
[ Speaking Italian ]
I'm -- No, I'm --

04:54.170 --> 04:55.290
[ Speaking Italian ]
Shut up.

04:55.290 --> 04:56.960
[ Speaking Italian ]
I'm not listening.

04:56.960 --> 04:58.460
[ Indistinct conversations,
telephone rings in distance ]

04:58.460 --> 04:59.750
Small apartment fire.

04:59.750 --> 05:01.920
This guy got
the worst of it.
[ Siren wailing ]

05:01.920 --> 05:03.670
Let's skip the trauma room and
head straight to the burn unit.

05:03.670 --> 05:04.620
[ Elevator bell dings ]
Hold the elevator!

05:04.620 --> 05:05.790
I can take him up.
I know the way.

05:05.790 --> 05:06.750
Thanks, Warren.

05:06.750 --> 05:08.670
[ Siren wails ]

05:08.670 --> 05:10.920
♪♪

05:10.920 --> 05:12.420
Bailey: Herrera,
what did you bring me?

05:12.420 --> 05:14.580
40-year-old female,
unconscious at the scene,

05:14.580 --> 05:17.830
persistently hypotensive,
pulse 120, resps 24.

05:17.830 --> 05:18.920
No evidence of trauma.

05:18.920 --> 05:20.210
Okay.
Any smoke inhalation?

05:20.210 --> 05:21.620
She wasn't even
in the fire.

05:21.620 --> 05:23.210
She was evacuated
with the other tenants,

05:23.210 --> 05:24.580
and then she collapsed
on the street outside.

05:24.580 --> 05:26.170
Let's get her inside.
Shoot. Where'd he go?

05:26.170 --> 05:28.880
Who?
Max -- her kid.
He was -- He was right here.

05:28.880 --> 05:32.500
♪♪

05:32.500 --> 05:34.750
You Max?

05:34.750 --> 05:37.040
Oh. You okay?
You -- You hurt?

05:37.040 --> 05:40.040
-[ Voice breaking ] No.
-Oh. Just scared?

05:40.040 --> 05:43.460
Yeah, uh, well, you don't
have to be scared.

05:43.460 --> 05:45.380
We're all gonna help
your mom, okay?

05:46.920 --> 05:48.960
You want to come
inside with me?

05:48.960 --> 05:52.380
♪♪

05:52.380 --> 05:54.420
Hey.

05:54.420 --> 06:04.500
♪♪

06:04.500 --> 06:05.670
[ Elevator bell dings ]

06:05.670 --> 06:07.500
[ Telephone ringing ]
[ Sighs ]

06:07.500 --> 06:08.830
Hey. No school?

06:08.830 --> 06:10.540
I have school.
I've been abducted.

06:10.540 --> 06:12.420
She's grounded.
But first we're --

06:12.420 --> 06:14.210
Uh, you're not my mom,
so this is not grounding.

06:14.210 --> 06:15.920
It's child abduction.
Go sit.

06:15.920 --> 06:18.250
Transport me across state lines,
it becomes a federal offense.

06:18.250 --> 06:19.880
[ Sighs ]

06:19.880 --> 06:22.580
Schmitt, would you get me
a 10-panel tox screen, please,

06:22.580 --> 06:25.210
right now?
Oh, I...

06:25.210 --> 06:26.210
Okay.

06:26.210 --> 06:28.330
Yes, ma'am.

06:28.330 --> 06:29.750
You brought her here
for a drug test

06:29.750 --> 06:30.920
and she went
along with it?

06:30.920 --> 06:32.460
Well, she doesn't
know yet.

06:32.460 --> 06:34.080
Uh, would you watch her?
I got to go change.

06:34.080 --> 06:35.540
Yep.

06:35.540 --> 06:37.460
Hey.

06:37.460 --> 06:39.540
[ Telephone ringing
in distance ]

06:39.540 --> 06:41.290
I seriously don't know how you
were ever married to her.

06:41.290 --> 06:42.830
She is so extra.
She is a little extra.

06:42.830 --> 06:44.750
Yeah, I agree.

06:44.750 --> 06:46.460
[ Sighs ] Meredith.
Hmm?

06:46.460 --> 06:49.830
If Zola got high, you would
ground her, right?

06:49.830 --> 06:52.210
-What?
-Look at you.

06:52.210 --> 06:54.250
What happened?
You have a funeral?
[ Door opens, closes ]

06:54.250 --> 06:55.920
What's wrong with you?
You look weird.

06:55.920 --> 06:57.420
Maggie: She's wearing makeup.
She looks pretty.

06:57.420 --> 06:58.880
Why?

06:58.880 --> 07:00.750
Oh, my God,
you have a date.

07:00.750 --> 07:02.620
Amelia:
Ah! You're doing it!

07:02.620 --> 07:04.120
Ah! You're letting
Mrs. Santa Claus

07:04.120 --> 07:05.460
bring you presents!

07:05.460 --> 07:07.420
All I got
was a lousy tree.

07:07.420 --> 07:08.460
Where are you going?

07:08.460 --> 07:10.120
Drinks? Coffee?
Lunch.

07:10.120 --> 07:11.790
Lunch? Lunch is boring.

07:11.790 --> 07:13.500
You can't make lunch
last all night.

07:13.500 --> 07:15.790
So, who is he?
Pics, please.

07:15.790 --> 07:17.920
No, no, that's not how
Mrs. Santa Claus works.

07:17.920 --> 07:19.460
No pictures.

07:19.460 --> 07:21.920
What's she hiding?
Neck beard? Man bun?

07:21.920 --> 07:23.880
Ear hair?
No.
She wants people to meet

07:23.880 --> 07:27.670
how they meet in real life --
with no preconceived notions.

07:27.670 --> 07:29.330
Scary. I like it.

07:29.330 --> 07:30.460
[ Pager beeping, vibrating ]
Damn it.

07:30.460 --> 07:31.670
Have fun.

07:31.670 --> 07:34.170
Cancel your afternoon --
for luck.

07:36.830 --> 07:37.880
♪♪

07:37.880 --> 07:39.170
[ Door closes ]

07:39.170 --> 07:40.540
What if I hate him
on sight?

07:40.540 --> 07:42.330
What's the minimum amount
of time this goes?

07:42.330 --> 07:44.120
Well, assuming your waiter
doesn't suck,

07:44.120 --> 07:45.790
a tight 30 minutes, if you don't
want to hurt his feelings.

07:45.790 --> 07:48.580
Okay.

07:48.580 --> 07:52.170
Five bucks says I can get out
in 20 and spare his feelings.

07:52.170 --> 07:53.460
All right, but no pretending
you get paged.

07:53.460 --> 07:54.540
That's cheating.

07:54.540 --> 07:56.330
It's $1 for every minute
you go over 20.

07:56.330 --> 07:58.000
I'll text you
in 20 minutes.

07:59.500 --> 08:00.750
Oh.

08:00.750 --> 08:03.120
Thank you for making it fun.

08:03.120 --> 08:04.040
[ Door closes ]

08:04.040 --> 08:05.920
[ Monitors beeping rapidly ]

08:05.920 --> 08:08.040
Hey, she just
went into V-fib.

08:08.040 --> 08:10.290
40-year-old female,
lost consciousness.

08:10.290 --> 08:12.120
[ Paddles whine ]
Charge to 200.

08:12.120 --> 08:13.710
Clear.
[ Thump ]

08:13.710 --> 08:14.790
[ Monitor beeping steadily ]

08:14.790 --> 08:16.040
[ Gasping ]

08:16.040 --> 08:18.170
Hey. Hey, Natalie.

08:18.170 --> 08:19.380
Okay. Back in sinus.

08:19.380 --> 08:20.460
Okay.

08:20.460 --> 08:22.620
You are in the hospital.
You passed out.

08:22.620 --> 08:25.460
[ Weakly ]
Max. Max!

08:25.460 --> 08:26.920
My son.

08:26.920 --> 08:28.210
Where's my son?

08:28.210 --> 08:29.540
Okay, Natalie,
I need you to be still.

08:29.540 --> 08:31.170
He's right out
in the waiting room.

08:31.170 --> 08:32.750
Bring him here.

08:32.750 --> 08:34.750
I need to see him.
I need to see he's okay.

08:34.750 --> 08:36.460
-Okay. X-ray's there.
-Okay.

08:36.460 --> 08:39.210
Sorry. It's just...

08:39.210 --> 08:42.080
Max likes to know
what's going on...

08:42.080 --> 08:44.830
to be told what's gonna happen,
or -- or he gets scared.

08:44.830 --> 08:45.960
I get that.

08:45.960 --> 08:47.710
He's coming.

08:47.710 --> 08:49.620
She has left ventricular
enlargement,

08:49.620 --> 08:51.790
pulmonary edema,
and a pleural effusion.

08:51.790 --> 08:53.330
We need a TEE.
Yep.

08:53.330 --> 08:56.500
[ Weakly ]
I just -- just need to...

08:56.500 --> 08:57.880
[ Gasps ]
Just...

08:57.880 --> 08:59.120
Natalie.
[ Monitor beeping rapidly ]

08:59.120 --> 09:00.420
Book an OR now.

09:00.420 --> 09:02.960
[ Rapid beeping continues ]

09:02.960 --> 09:04.420
[ Voice breaking ]
Mom!

09:04.420 --> 09:05.960
Mom!
DeLuca:
Max, Max, come here.

09:05.960 --> 09:07.710
Mom! Mom!
Hey, please. Come on.

09:07.710 --> 09:08.710
♪♪

09:23.580 --> 09:30.250
♪♪

09:30.250 --> 09:36.960
♪♪

09:36.960 --> 09:42.960
[ Indistinct conversations ]

09:44.210 --> 09:46.250
Sorry. Hey. Are you --
Hi. Jon?

09:46.250 --> 09:47.790
Yes. Hi.
Hi.

09:47.790 --> 09:49.040
Uh, they said there's
a bit of a wait,

09:49.040 --> 09:50.170
but we can sit at the bar.

09:50.170 --> 09:52.670
Okay.
Let's start the clock.

09:52.670 --> 09:55.420
I just meant -- I mean,
let's just get started.

09:55.420 --> 09:57.830
[ Chuckling ]
Yeah. Okay.

09:57.830 --> 10:00.040
[ Clears throat ]
All right.

10:00.040 --> 10:01.540
That's a nice coat.
Thank you.

10:01.540 --> 10:02.540
Nice purse.
Thanks.

10:02.540 --> 10:04.120
The whole thing's working.
Thank you.

10:07.420 --> 10:10.540
You -- Oh, uh, Max,
we called your dad.

10:10.540 --> 10:12.500
He's on his way.
Your mom is stable.

10:12.500 --> 10:14.250
She's getting prepped
for surgery right now.

10:14.250 --> 10:17.380
Uh, and a nice woman
is on her way to sit with you.

10:17.380 --> 10:20.620
I'll sit with you, Max, until
the social worker gets here.

10:20.620 --> 10:23.620
Oh, thanks.
Okay, uh, I'll be back soon.

10:23.620 --> 10:25.250
[ Clears throat ]

10:25.250 --> 10:27.080
Did you just put us
on babysitting duty?

10:27.080 --> 10:29.120
We have to get checked
by a doctor

10:29.120 --> 10:30.960
after every fire incident now,
anyway, so...

10:30.960 --> 10:32.790
Um, are we really
doing that?

10:32.790 --> 10:33.710
Captain's orders.

10:33.710 --> 10:36.420
Sit.

10:36.420 --> 10:39.330
[ Radio chatter ]

10:39.330 --> 10:42.000
I'm good, guys, yeah.
I'm not even burnt.

10:42.000 --> 10:43.960
I was just delivering food.

10:43.960 --> 10:47.000
Not even my building.
It's not even my fire.

10:47.000 --> 10:48.500
And if the smoke got
into your lungs...

10:48.500 --> 10:50.000
Got to take a look.

10:50.000 --> 10:52.000
It says here your emergency
contact is your mom?

10:52.000 --> 10:53.710
No, don't call my mom!

10:53.710 --> 10:55.290
No, she -- she lives in Philly.
She'll just worry.

10:55.290 --> 10:57.540
Also, uh, I go to U-Dub,

10:57.540 --> 10:59.880
and I have class in an hour,
so, uh, I should --

10:59.880 --> 11:01.250
I'll write you a note.
Open wide.

11:01.250 --> 11:03.170
I have a chem test.
Say, "Ahh."

11:03.170 --> 11:05.210
[ Muffled ]
Also, it's a makeup test.

11:05.210 --> 11:06.710
It's like
a make-it-or-break-it.

11:06.710 --> 11:08.000
It's my last chance.

11:08.000 --> 11:09.120
I should just go.

11:09.120 --> 11:11.250
You need
a chest X-ray first.

11:11.250 --> 11:13.330
X-rays?
Doesn't that cost extra?

11:13.330 --> 11:14.880
Oh, you don't need
to worry about that.

11:14.880 --> 11:16.040
Wait. But...

11:17.290 --> 11:19.500
[ Indistinct conversations ]

11:19.500 --> 11:21.040
Max. Buddy.

11:21.040 --> 11:23.120
Dad!
Where's Mom?

11:23.120 --> 11:25.040
Hi. Are you
Natalie's husband?

11:25.040 --> 11:27.080
Yeah. Uh, Evan.
Evan Forrester.

11:27.080 --> 11:29.330
Hey. I'm Dr. Bailey.
This is Dr. Pierce.
Hi.

11:29.330 --> 11:31.670
Um, has your wife been
complaining of any heart --

11:31.670 --> 11:33.500
H-Hang on. Sorry.

11:33.500 --> 11:34.960
Go ahead. Sit down, son.
It's okay.

11:34.960 --> 11:36.670
Go ahead.
[ Whimpers ]

11:36.670 --> 11:38.670
Woman on P.A.:
Dr. Bradshaw, call Recovery.

11:38.670 --> 11:40.420
Dr. Bradshaw, call Recovery.

11:40.420 --> 11:42.250
We think your wife had
a recent heart attack,

11:42.250 --> 11:43.960
and now the wall between the
two main chambers of her heart

11:43.960 --> 11:46.040
has ruptured.
Is it --

11:46.040 --> 11:47.380
We won't know
how much damage there is

11:47.380 --> 11:49.750
until we can get in there,
but we will keep you updated.

11:49.750 --> 11:51.120
Okay?
Okay.

11:51.120 --> 11:53.330
Um, hey.

11:53.330 --> 11:54.460
[ Whimpers ]

11:54.460 --> 11:56.580
I know you like to know
what's going on.

11:56.580 --> 11:59.960
Okay, so, we're gonna take your
mom to the operating room, okay?

11:59.960 --> 12:01.540
She's having some trouble
with her heart,

12:01.540 --> 12:04.960
but we are gonna do everything
we can to fix her, okay?

12:04.960 --> 12:06.380
Okay.

12:06.380 --> 12:08.420
Okay.

12:08.420 --> 12:11.290
Dr. Monroe, call the pharmacy.
Dr. Monroe, call the pharmacy.

12:11.290 --> 12:13.290
Well, I think
we're good to go.

12:13.290 --> 12:14.750
Are we in that big
of a rush?

12:14.750 --> 12:18.170
I kind of want to see how
the kid's mom comes out.

12:18.170 --> 12:20.380
And what was
her name again?

12:20.380 --> 12:21.670
Uh...
The cardio doc.

12:21.670 --> 12:23.830
Dr. Pierce.

12:23.830 --> 12:25.880
Dean. Really?

12:25.880 --> 12:27.500
Did you see that woman?

12:27.500 --> 12:29.120
Did you see her
self-assuredness,

12:29.120 --> 12:30.880
her compassion for children,

12:30.880 --> 12:33.710
and her very,
very nice eyes?

12:33.710 --> 12:36.540
Look, we also got to wait
for a doctor's check, right?

12:36.540 --> 12:38.500
Oh, now you want
to do that? Mm.

12:38.500 --> 12:39.710
Mm-hmm. Captain's orders.

12:41.880 --> 12:44.290
Hey! You still here?

12:44.290 --> 12:46.670
Hey. Yeah.
Just, uh -- Just heading out.

12:46.670 --> 12:48.500
What have you got
in your hand?

12:48.500 --> 12:50.670
I-I don't have anything
in my hand.

12:50.670 --> 12:53.250
Show me your hand.

12:53.250 --> 12:54.790
[ Laughs ]

12:54.790 --> 12:57.330
Uh, i-it's nothing.

12:57.330 --> 12:59.330
I-It's nothing,
a little burn.

12:59.330 --> 13:01.880
[ Chuckles ]
I had to check a door for heat.

13:01.880 --> 13:03.830
It's my first injury.
[ Chuckles ]

13:03.830 --> 13:05.460
Had to happen sometime.

13:05.460 --> 13:07.040
[ Smooches ]

13:10.250 --> 13:13.170
You see this thin sac in
the wall of Julius' lung?

13:13.170 --> 13:14.880
He's got a pulmonary bleb.

13:14.880 --> 13:16.920
Ugh. "Bleb."

13:16.920 --> 13:19.420
It's air trapped in
the lining of the lung.

13:19.420 --> 13:21.880
Yeah, I know what it is.
I just hate how it sounds --

13:21.880 --> 13:23.120
"bleb."
[ Computer beeping ]

13:23.120 --> 13:25.670
-What's it stand for?
-It doesn't. It's a word.

13:25.670 --> 13:28.460
It's not a word.
It's a sound effect.

13:28.460 --> 13:29.460
"Bleb."

13:29.460 --> 13:30.880
Well, if it bursts,

13:30.880 --> 13:32.880
his lung collapses,
and Julius dies.

13:34.670 --> 13:35.830
[ Sighs ]

13:35.830 --> 13:37.620
It should be
a less funny word.

13:39.040 --> 13:40.380
Suction.
[ Liquid suctioning ]

13:40.380 --> 13:43.580
Bailey: Now, what
is Avery doing, exactly?

13:43.580 --> 13:47.420
I don't --
Um, something to do with God,

13:47.420 --> 13:49.790
uh, and a tree.

13:49.790 --> 13:50.580
Like a sabbatical?

13:50.580 --> 13:52.120
Yeah. Yeah.

13:52.120 --> 13:55.210
Uh, exactly, like a --
a spiritual sabbatical.

13:55.210 --> 13:56.830
Where he just
decides overnight

13:56.830 --> 13:58.710
to run off
and do what he wants?

13:58.710 --> 14:00.750
Yeah, sounds like
spiritual spring break.

14:04.290 --> 14:06.830
Oh, damn it.
Damn it.

14:06.830 --> 14:09.710
You see there?
That is a big ventricular
septal rupture.

14:09.710 --> 14:11.830
She probably had a heart attack
a week ago,

14:11.830 --> 14:13.080
thought it
was indigestion,

14:13.080 --> 14:14.880
and now it's just been weakening
ever since.

14:14.880 --> 14:16.670
-Irrigation.
-Yeah.

14:16.670 --> 14:18.830
-What do you want to do?
-I want to close the defect.

14:18.830 --> 14:19.880
Bovine patch.

14:19.880 --> 14:21.620
Herrera said she was down
for a while.

14:23.380 --> 14:25.830
I know, but I -- I don't
want to go down there

14:25.830 --> 14:27.920
and tell that little boy
that his mother is gone.

14:29.460 --> 14:34.380
Uh, let's try a temporary LVAD
and...hope.

14:34.380 --> 14:37.120
♪♪

14:43.420 --> 14:44.420
So, you're in software?
Mm-hmm.

14:44.420 --> 14:46.210
Where is the T-shirt
and hoodie?

14:46.210 --> 14:47.790
I know. I tried.

14:47.790 --> 14:49.750
It just feels like wearing
your pajamas to work,

14:49.750 --> 14:51.330
you know?
I do know.

14:51.330 --> 14:53.420
I actually wear my pajamas
to work, sort of.

14:53.420 --> 14:55.040
I'm a surgeon.
You are?

14:55.040 --> 14:56.830
Mm-hmm.
What kind?

14:56.830 --> 14:59.330
Um, I'm Chief of General
at Grey-Sloan.

14:59.330 --> 15:00.500
Wow.

15:00.500 --> 15:01.880
So, you're a big deal.

15:01.880 --> 15:02.960
Oh, yeah.

15:02.960 --> 15:04.120
What kind of software?

15:04.120 --> 15:06.170
I'm not supposed
to tell you.

15:06.170 --> 15:07.580
It's privacy stuff.

15:07.580 --> 15:09.710
Oh. I get it.

15:09.710 --> 15:13.500
No, I mean, it's, uh,
actually privacy software.

15:13.500 --> 15:14.620
Oh.
I'm telling you.

15:14.620 --> 15:17.330
I don't care.
I'm terrible at keeping secrets.

15:17.330 --> 15:18.420
I just think
we should be able to decide

15:18.420 --> 15:20.210
what we want to tell the world
about ourselves

15:20.210 --> 15:22.290
and who should
get to see it.

15:22.290 --> 15:24.250
My software
lets you do that.

15:24.250 --> 15:25.580
That's all.
Oh.

15:25.580 --> 15:28.420
So, you're not mining
people's data or...

15:28.420 --> 15:31.080
The opposite, actually --
protecting it.

15:31.080 --> 15:33.250
Mm.
Here's to the good guys.

15:33.250 --> 15:35.080
I mean, I'm not cutting
people's cancer out

15:35.080 --> 15:36.830
in my pajamas or anything,
but...

15:36.830 --> 15:38.120
Mm.
But you do what you can.

15:38.120 --> 15:39.830
I do what I can.
[ Laughs ]

15:41.420 --> 15:43.580
Look, if it bursts,
your lung could collapse.

15:43.580 --> 15:44.880
It puts you at risk.

15:44.880 --> 15:46.420
I know.
I know all about my bleb.

15:46.420 --> 15:48.000
I've had it since
I was a baby.

15:48.000 --> 15:49.080
Why do you guys
call it that?

15:49.080 --> 15:51.500
[ Chuckling ]
Right?

15:51.500 --> 15:53.960
Anyway, I'm not doing
a marathon anytime soon,

15:53.960 --> 15:55.880
unless it's video games.

15:55.880 --> 15:58.500
I'm okay.
I get along fine.
Yeah, until now.

15:58.500 --> 16:00.380
The smoke you inhaled is making
your lungs work harder.

16:00.380 --> 16:02.670
And your bleb is making them
work too hard.

16:02.670 --> 16:04.120
But I can operate.
I can take it out for good.

16:04.120 --> 16:05.460
No. No surgery.

16:05.460 --> 16:06.710
My mom's insurance --

16:06.710 --> 16:08.830
it -- it only covers
emergency-room visits.

16:08.830 --> 16:10.830
My stupid bleb's
a pre-existing condition.

16:10.830 --> 16:13.080
If we called your mom, she would
say, "Let's figure it out."

16:13.080 --> 16:14.750
No. No, my mom already
works three jobs

16:14.750 --> 16:16.540
just to keep me
in food and clothes, okay?

16:16.540 --> 16:19.170
The surgery will -- will put us
20 grand in the hole.

16:19.170 --> 16:21.040
Just let me out of here,
or --

16:21.040 --> 16:22.540
or I'll talk to
your supervisor, okay?

16:24.080 --> 16:26.170
I am my supervisor.

16:26.170 --> 16:28.500
Well --
Well, don't call my mom.

16:28.500 --> 16:31.210
If you tell my mom,
I'll sue you guys.

16:31.210 --> 16:33.250
Then all of our money problems
will be gone.

16:33.250 --> 16:34.170
Okay?

16:35.880 --> 16:38.670
Can't we just take
it out, anyway?
Kid's 18.

16:38.670 --> 16:40.170
Doing it anyway
would be assault.

16:40.170 --> 16:42.460
Start him on continuous
nebs and 40% O2

16:42.460 --> 16:44.750
and, uh, slow-roll
his discharge.
Okay.

16:44.750 --> 16:46.710
[ Clears throat ]

16:46.710 --> 16:48.460
We need to talk
about last night.

16:48.460 --> 16:49.500
That was insulting.

16:49.500 --> 16:51.420
Oh, it was, and I accept
your apology.

16:51.420 --> 16:53.500
You need to apologize to me,
dummy.

16:53.500 --> 16:54.500
I don't have sex with you

16:54.500 --> 16:55.460
because I want stuff
from the chief.

16:55.460 --> 16:57.500
I have sex with you 'cause
I want one thing from you --

16:57.500 --> 16:58.830
orgasms!

17:00.080 --> 17:01.790
And maybe you should tell me

17:01.790 --> 17:03.210
when Webber's
standing behind me

17:03.210 --> 17:05.120
so I don't say things
like that.

17:05.120 --> 17:06.920
[ Chuckles nervously ]

17:09.620 --> 17:11.120
[ Sighs ]

17:11.120 --> 17:13.790
You...paged me, Karev?

17:13.790 --> 17:15.000
Has Schmitt
been back yet?

17:15.000 --> 17:16.250
Uh, haven't seen him.

17:16.250 --> 17:17.710
What are we even
doing here?

17:17.710 --> 17:19.460
Dr. Shepherd,
here you go.

17:19.460 --> 17:20.830
Sorry it took so long.

17:20.830 --> 17:22.460
I have
a really shy bladder.

17:22.460 --> 17:26.290
What? Why?
Whose is -- Why?

17:26.290 --> 17:27.710
You said you wanted
a drug test.

17:27.710 --> 17:29.420
I figured because
of that time with the cookies,

17:29.420 --> 17:31.880
but I am not --
Not from you.

17:31.880 --> 17:33.170
For her!
Yeah.

17:34.750 --> 17:36.380
I am so sorry.

17:36.380 --> 17:38.380
Hey, hey, hey.
Take that with you, please.

17:38.380 --> 17:39.620
You brought me here
for a drug test?

17:39.620 --> 17:41.620
What the hell?!
Whoa, whoa -- workplace.

17:41.620 --> 17:43.080
You're not lying,
so what's the big deal?

17:43.080 --> 17:44.830
The big deal
is you trusting me

17:44.830 --> 17:46.080
and not treating me
like a criminal.

17:46.080 --> 17:47.750
Hey. Wh--
Where are you going?

17:47.750 --> 17:50.080
To daycare,
to see Leo. Geez!

17:52.670 --> 17:54.000
[ Telephone ringing
in distance ]

17:54.000 --> 17:55.620
[ Sighs ]
This is stupid.

17:55.620 --> 17:57.380
We're going.
Hey, we're waiting
to get checked.

17:57.380 --> 17:59.210
No. We were waiting.
Now we're stalking.

17:59.210 --> 18:01.080
Any doctor
can check us out.

18:01.080 --> 18:04.420
Hey.
That's her. That's her.

18:04.420 --> 18:05.880
Maggie:
Mr. Forrester.

18:09.750 --> 18:12.500
Uh, Natalie's
out of surgery.

18:12.500 --> 18:16.670
But the damage to her heart
was very severe.

18:16.670 --> 18:18.790
And we had some trouble
getting her off the pump.

18:18.790 --> 18:21.170
I'm so sorry,

18:21.170 --> 18:22.920
but there is only
a slim chance

18:22.920 --> 18:25.040
that Natalie
will wake up again.

18:25.040 --> 18:27.290
[ Breathes deeply ]

18:27.290 --> 18:29.500
Look, uh, take a few minutes
to talk to your son,

18:29.500 --> 18:32.790
and, um, we'll -- we'll
take you to see her.

18:32.790 --> 18:34.040
Dad.

18:34.040 --> 18:35.750
Max.

18:35.750 --> 18:37.040
I-Is Mom okay?

18:37.040 --> 18:39.670
Uh, she's, uh --

18:39.670 --> 18:42.290
Mom is, uh...

18:44.460 --> 18:49.380
Max...your mom
was really badly hurt.

18:49.380 --> 18:50.750
And we did everything
we could to help --

18:50.750 --> 18:53.290
And it's gonna be
all right.

18:53.290 --> 18:55.710
She's gonna be all right.

18:55.710 --> 18:57.120
Right?

18:57.120 --> 18:58.580
[ Whimpers ]

18:58.580 --> 19:03.500
♪♪

19:09.960 --> 19:10.830
I mean,
dating's not that bad.

19:10.830 --> 19:11.920
I like talking to people...

19:11.920 --> 19:14.000
till you hit
the One Thing.

19:14.000 --> 19:15.420
What's the One Thing?

19:15.420 --> 19:17.580
Date's going great,
right?

19:17.580 --> 19:20.460
She's smart, you're funny,
you're -- you're hitting it off.

19:20.460 --> 19:22.080
And then she says
the One Thing,

19:22.080 --> 19:24.290
right, the one, uh,
slightly racist thing.

19:24.290 --> 19:26.080
Oh, oh.
Right? Or she, uh --

19:26.080 --> 19:27.210
she tears down
her co-workers

19:27.210 --> 19:29.620
or uses the wrong word
for gay people

19:29.620 --> 19:33.000
or misuses "their," "they're,"
and "there" in a text.

19:33.000 --> 19:34.330
That's unforgivable.
Totally.

19:34.330 --> 19:37.080
I mean, the One Thing
ends the date,

19:37.080 --> 19:38.830
even if you're stuck there
for another hour.

19:38.830 --> 19:40.540
This is why I don't date.

19:40.540 --> 19:42.460
I imagine you're also kind of
married to work.

19:42.460 --> 19:44.330
I have been accused
of that, yeah.

19:44.330 --> 19:46.420
No, wait.
W-Why is that an accusation?

19:46.420 --> 19:48.790
It takes a ton of focus for
someone to get where you are,

19:48.790 --> 19:50.420
as young as you are.

19:50.420 --> 19:51.790
Some people
don't like their partner

19:51.790 --> 19:53.120
to be as committed
to their work

19:53.120 --> 19:54.210
as they are
to their relationship.

19:54.210 --> 19:55.330
I just don't get it.

19:55.330 --> 19:56.710
Is that why you're single?

19:56.710 --> 19:58.620
Yeah.
My wife couldn't share.

19:58.620 --> 20:00.120
You?

20:00.120 --> 20:02.460
Mm, he could share,
but he died.

20:03.670 --> 20:06.540
I'm sorry.
Thank you.

20:06.540 --> 20:08.120
Yeah.

20:08.120 --> 20:10.500
Work's a very forgiving partner,
but it doesn't really --

20:10.500 --> 20:12.620
Throw you up against the wall
and kiss you.

20:12.620 --> 20:15.000
I was gonna say scratch your
back, but I like yours, too.

20:15.000 --> 20:17.040
[ Both chuckle ]

20:19.420 --> 20:21.830
Actually, if you don't mind,
I'm just going to,

20:21.830 --> 20:24.750
uh, call work and move some
things around this afternoon.

20:24.750 --> 20:26.080
Yeah, sure. Okay.
Okay.

20:26.080 --> 20:28.460
[ Indistinct conversations ]

20:28.460 --> 20:29.830
[ Cellphone keys clicking ]

20:32.830 --> 20:35.380
Oh, God.
What?

20:35.380 --> 20:38.460
This is, um -- I'm sorry
to have to tell you this.

20:38.460 --> 20:41.330
I-I thought you didn't
look like your picture,

20:41.330 --> 20:43.830
and it's because
it's, um --

20:43.830 --> 20:45.460
it's her picture.

20:48.120 --> 20:49.960
Yeah. I'm supposed to be
on a date with her.

20:49.960 --> 20:52.460
Are you Jon?
Yeah. I am.

20:52.460 --> 20:54.210
But it's
a pretty common name.

20:54.210 --> 20:55.830
Do you want
to go over there?

20:55.830 --> 20:58.420
I don't.
I'm enjoying this.

20:58.420 --> 21:00.460
[ Chuckles ]
Well, she looks like

21:00.460 --> 21:02.750
she's having a good time
over there.

21:02.750 --> 21:06.880
So...do you think
that's my Jon?

21:08.880 --> 21:11.330
[ Both laugh ]

21:12.750 --> 21:14.120
Richard: You call his mother,
you break HIPAA.

21:14.120 --> 21:16.120
You break HIPAA,
we get sued.

21:16.120 --> 21:18.880
[ Sighs ]
So, what do I do?

21:18.880 --> 21:21.080
You know, Karev,
the only thing less fun

21:21.080 --> 21:22.080
than watching you
do this job

21:22.080 --> 21:23.670
is doing it for you.

21:23.670 --> 21:25.000
Look, this isn't
a chief thing.

21:25.000 --> 21:26.080
This --
I-It -- It is.

21:26.080 --> 21:27.580
I mean,
being chief is...

21:27.580 --> 21:29.420
nothing but
being backed into corners.

21:29.420 --> 21:32.000
The trick is finding
creative ways to get out.

21:32.000 --> 21:32.960
Well,
then I've found one.

21:32.960 --> 21:34.290
I'm telling Bailey I quit.

21:34.290 --> 21:35.960
You can have
this stupid job.
No.

21:35.960 --> 21:37.080
No, you have been
pissy about this

21:37.080 --> 21:38.500
since the day I started.

21:38.500 --> 21:40.420
I mean you are not allowed
to quit, okay?

21:40.420 --> 21:42.210
You may only quit
after you've done it

21:42.210 --> 21:45.080
to the best of your ability
and decided to, okay?

21:45.080 --> 21:46.120
Otherwise,
it's not quitting.

21:46.120 --> 21:47.420
It's failing.

21:47.420 --> 21:50.420
Now, my mother told me that,
and it's true.

21:50.420 --> 21:52.120
So, what were you quitting --
med school?

21:52.120 --> 21:53.250
I didn't want to
play tetherball.

21:53.250 --> 21:54.620
I was 10.

21:54.620 --> 21:55.750
This isn't tetherball.

21:55.750 --> 21:57.420
Oh, it's all tetherball,
Karev.

21:57.420 --> 21:58.920
Look, kick its ass

21:58.920 --> 22:00.830
and then decide
you don't want it.

22:00.830 --> 22:02.830
Don't let it decide
it doesn't want you.

22:02.830 --> 22:05.210
I -- Aah!

22:05.210 --> 22:07.000
[ Telephone rings in distance ]

22:07.000 --> 22:08.250
[ Indistinct conversations ]

22:09.880 --> 22:11.210
Ah.
We get our doc checks

22:11.210 --> 22:13.380
from the chief of surgery?

22:13.380 --> 22:15.000
Is that the best
use of resources?

22:15.000 --> 22:16.830
I'm on sabbatical.
[ Beeps ]

22:16.830 --> 22:18.830
You look good.
Miller, sit.

22:18.830 --> 22:20.120
The right finger.

22:20.120 --> 22:22.750
He was hoping
for Dr. Pierce.

22:22.750 --> 22:24.830
Open.
[ Flashlight clicks ]

22:24.830 --> 22:26.920
Ah.
Um, do you --
do you know --

22:26.920 --> 22:29.210
do you know if
she's single -- Dr. Pierce?

22:29.210 --> 22:30.580
Do I look like your auntie,
Miller?

22:30.580 --> 22:33.330
[ Beeps ]
All right,
you're all checked out.

22:33.330 --> 22:34.880
[ Sighs ]

22:34.880 --> 22:37.000
Uh, hey, question --

22:37.000 --> 22:39.290
who was first
into this apartment fire?

22:39.290 --> 22:41.040
-It was...Warren and Hughes.
-War-- Warren.

22:41.040 --> 22:43.750
Why?
Was that the best
use of resources?

22:43.750 --> 22:47.420
I mean, he's the only surgeon
on a team of firefighters.

22:47.420 --> 22:49.170
Don't you want
to protect those hands?

22:52.880 --> 22:55.830
"So sorry. I would never want
to stand you up."

22:55.830 --> 22:57.080
"Something has come up."

22:57.080 --> 23:01.380
"Something unavoidable
has come up,

23:01.380 --> 23:04.790
and I can't
make it there."

23:04.790 --> 23:06.540
That look good?

23:06.540 --> 23:08.580
Yep. But just change
the "there"

23:08.580 --> 23:10.290
to the wrong "their" --
that'll soften the blow.

23:10.290 --> 23:12.210
Oh, that is good.
[ Laughs ]

23:12.210 --> 23:13.830
Okay? One, two, three.
Yep.

23:13.830 --> 23:15.380
[ Cellphones beep ]

23:15.380 --> 23:17.080
[ Cellphones chime ]

23:17.080 --> 23:19.670
[ Indistinct conversations ]

23:19.670 --> 23:20.960
[ Laughs ]

23:20.960 --> 23:23.080
And just like that,
we're yesterday's news.

23:23.080 --> 23:25.460
Maybe they're
falling in love.

23:25.460 --> 23:27.670
Maybe this is
meant to be.

23:27.670 --> 23:28.790
Good luck to them.

23:28.790 --> 23:31.250
We should, uh --
We should get out of here

23:31.250 --> 23:33.250
before they see us.
Okay.

23:33.250 --> 23:36.960
♪♪

23:36.960 --> 23:38.380
Just --
Be cool.

23:38.380 --> 23:39.790
Yeah, just be cool,
will you?
Yeah. Mm-hmm.

23:39.790 --> 23:41.290
You're just freaking out
right now.
Okay.

23:41.290 --> 23:42.420
You're drawing a lot
of attention to us.

23:42.420 --> 23:43.420
[ Chuckles ]
Go. Go. Go.

23:44.620 --> 23:46.580
It's not fair.
When Leo is 15,

23:46.580 --> 23:48.830
you'll have had 14 years
to get ready.

23:48.830 --> 23:50.620
Mm. If I get
to keep him.

23:50.620 --> 23:52.420
Okay.
I'm just saying,

23:52.420 --> 23:54.170
I don't know how
to discipline a teenager.

23:54.170 --> 23:55.540
You were one.

23:55.540 --> 23:56.620
What did your mom do?

23:56.620 --> 23:58.750
Nothing.
Wh--

23:58.750 --> 24:00.960
She ruled with an iron fist
over her first four kids,

24:00.960 --> 24:03.460
but I was her kryptonite.

24:03.460 --> 24:06.040
I think once my father died
in front of me,

24:06.040 --> 24:08.580
she was afraid
to upset me.

24:08.580 --> 24:10.920
She just let me do
whatever I wanted.

24:10.920 --> 24:11.710
Oh, my mom
was the opposite.

24:11.710 --> 24:13.170
When my dad died,

24:13.170 --> 24:15.380
she became Mom, Dad,
judge, jury, and executioner

24:15.380 --> 24:16.750
for me and Megan.

24:16.750 --> 24:18.040
Yeah. [ Chuckles ]

24:18.040 --> 24:20.710
Well...
you turned out okay.

24:20.710 --> 24:23.210
Eh. I hope so.

24:23.210 --> 24:25.500
[ Exhales deeply ]

24:25.500 --> 24:28.750
You know, sometimes I think
parenting -- it's just...

24:28.750 --> 24:30.710
Okay, fine.
[ Scoffs ]

24:34.920 --> 24:36.750
Whoa. What?

24:37.830 --> 24:40.080
Hey.

24:40.080 --> 24:42.290
Hey, Max, what are you
doing down here?

24:45.000 --> 24:46.830
Is my mom
gonna be okay?

24:49.000 --> 24:50.210
Max.

24:53.460 --> 24:57.170
Um, Max, the problem...

24:57.170 --> 25:00.250
that your mom has
is a big one.

25:00.250 --> 25:03.420
So, her heart, which pumps
all the blood through her body,

25:03.420 --> 25:05.080
is pretty badly damaged.
[ Footsteps approaching ]

25:05.080 --> 25:07.080
It's -- It's --
There you are!

25:07.080 --> 25:09.580
You can't go running off
like that, buddy, please.

25:09.580 --> 25:11.250
She was telling me
about Mom.

25:11.250 --> 25:12.710
Is there a change?

25:12.710 --> 25:14.500
Can I speak to you
for a sec?

25:15.670 --> 25:17.080
Look, I-I just went
to the restroom,

25:17.080 --> 25:19.710
and -- and -- and when
he's scared, he likes to hide.

25:19.710 --> 25:21.750
Yeah. Um...

25:21.750 --> 25:23.380
he probably gets that
from you.

25:25.040 --> 25:28.290
I'm sorry?
Look, I know
you're trying to protect Max,

25:28.290 --> 25:30.830
but he needs to know
what's coming.

25:30.830 --> 25:31.920
You don't know my kid.

25:31.920 --> 25:34.170
I know that any kid
needs to be prepared

25:34.170 --> 25:35.960
for what is going to happen
to his mother.

25:35.960 --> 25:37.710
You said
there's still a chance.

25:37.710 --> 25:39.000
I said
there was a slim chance.

25:39.000 --> 25:41.960
That's still a chance!

25:41.960 --> 25:44.830
Max, let's go, buddy.

25:44.830 --> 25:48.120
And I'm not gonna
take that away from him.

25:48.120 --> 25:49.710
Please don't
talk to my son.

25:51.380 --> 25:53.040
Woman on P.A.:
Dr. Hoffman to Oncology.

25:53.040 --> 25:55.120
Dr. Hoffman to Oncology.

25:56.330 --> 25:57.420
What happened?

25:57.420 --> 25:58.830
Dahlia:
He's trying to leave.

25:58.830 --> 26:00.120
He got winded
putting on his pants.

26:00.120 --> 26:01.920
[ Sighs ] It's because
your lungs aren't working right.

26:01.920 --> 26:03.830
Come on, pal.

26:03.830 --> 26:06.000
His pulse ox
was just 88 on room air.

26:06.000 --> 26:07.920
[ Sighs ] Look, Julius, you
still haven't recovered fully

26:07.920 --> 26:09.540
from the smoke inhalation.

26:09.540 --> 26:12.330
And this bleb -- it -- it --
it could burst out there,

26:12.330 --> 26:14.670
in the middle of chem class,
when I'm not there to help you.

26:14.670 --> 26:15.920
[ Breathing heavily ]
The insurance --

26:15.920 --> 26:17.710
it was really c-clear.

26:17.710 --> 26:19.460
This was pre-exi--
existing.

26:19.460 --> 26:21.170
I-I can't afford this.

26:21.170 --> 26:22.380
I got to go.

26:22.380 --> 26:25.920
[ Indistinct conversations ]

26:25.920 --> 26:28.670
Okay, uh, just,
uh, um, lie back.

26:28.670 --> 26:29.830
Let me check you
before you leave.

26:29.830 --> 26:32.500
Wait. Le--
H-He's just gonna leave AMA?

26:32.500 --> 26:35.040
Yeah. He's allowed
to refuse care.

26:35.040 --> 26:37.670
Legally, we can't force you
to have treatment.

26:37.670 --> 26:40.750
[ Grunts ]

26:40.750 --> 26:41.880
What is this?

26:41.880 --> 26:44.000
♪♪

26:44.000 --> 26:45.040
W-What did you do?

26:45.040 --> 26:47.170
He has a penetrating
chest wound.

26:47.170 --> 26:48.710
I mean,
how did we miss this?

26:48.710 --> 26:51.080
I didn't.
Well, I mean,
it's right there.

26:51.080 --> 26:53.000
I mean, this could be
invading the pleural space.

26:53.000 --> 26:54.620
We got to take a look
in surgery.

26:54.620 --> 26:56.290
No, I-I can't have surgery.

26:56.290 --> 26:58.830
Dude, listen,
it's an emergency surgery,

26:58.830 --> 27:01.380
so it's covered
under your insurance...

27:01.380 --> 27:04.710
and anything else
that we find in there.

27:04.710 --> 27:06.500
Do you understand?

27:06.500 --> 27:07.880
Yeah.

27:07.880 --> 27:08.750
All right. Okay.

27:08.750 --> 27:10.250
All right, Qadri, um,

27:10.250 --> 27:12.540
send off pre-op labs
and book an OR.

27:12.540 --> 27:13.790
♪♪

27:13.790 --> 27:15.790
Dr. Karev...

27:15.790 --> 27:17.540
I have to report this.

27:17.540 --> 27:19.170
Well, you just told
the chief.

27:19.170 --> 27:21.120
♪♪

27:27.620 --> 27:28.750
[ Indistinct conversations ]

27:28.750 --> 27:30.750
Mom? Mom, are you okay?
What do you need?

27:30.750 --> 27:32.250
Nothing.
I'm not here to see you.

27:32.250 --> 27:34.250
I have a life, Owen.
Good Lord.

27:34.250 --> 27:35.540
[ Indistinct conversations ]

27:35.540 --> 27:37.210
No. We're going, Miller.

27:37.210 --> 27:39.080
We -- We've hung around
long enough.

27:39.080 --> 27:41.170
But we should tell Dr. Pierce
we're leaving, though, right?

27:41.170 --> 27:41.880
You know,
close the circle.

27:41.880 --> 27:43.960
Hey, Dr. Pierce.

27:43.960 --> 27:45.330
-Hey.
-Hey.

27:47.620 --> 27:50.170
Uh, Dean.
Miller. Dean.

27:50.170 --> 27:52.250
Ah.

27:52.250 --> 27:55.380
What's up?
Uh...I was wondering

27:55.380 --> 27:57.670
how that lady was doing,

27:57.670 --> 27:59.080
the -- that
poor kid's mom.

27:59.080 --> 28:01.750
Oh. Yeah, not good.
Mnh.

28:01.750 --> 28:03.460
There was too much damage
to repair.

28:03.460 --> 28:05.670
Wow.
That's...too bad.

28:05.670 --> 28:06.880
Yeah.

28:06.880 --> 28:12.960
♪♪

28:12.960 --> 28:13.710
Was there something else?

28:13.710 --> 28:15.120
Uh, yes, yes.

28:15.120 --> 28:18.830
Um, just trying
to pivot from that.

28:18.830 --> 28:21.170
I kind of
set myself up badly.

28:21.170 --> 28:22.830
For?
I was -- I was --
I was wondering

28:22.830 --> 28:25.830
if you would like to
get dinner with me sometime.

28:25.830 --> 28:27.120
Oh.

28:27.120 --> 28:28.170
[ Laughing ] Oh!

28:28.170 --> 28:32.920
Um...well, Dean...
[ Laughs ]

28:32.920 --> 28:34.170
Don't have to laugh.

28:34.170 --> 28:36.580
No, no, I just --
[ Laughs ]

28:36.580 --> 28:41.040
I, uh -- I had a fiancé
named Dean once.

28:41.040 --> 28:43.460
This is --
This is going great.

28:43.460 --> 28:44.830
DeLuca: Dr. Pierce...
[breathing heavily]

28:44.830 --> 28:46.040
Natalie Forrester
coded again.

28:46.040 --> 28:47.750
We brought her back,
but she's circling the drain.

28:47.750 --> 28:49.330
[ Sighs ]
I have to go.

28:51.460 --> 28:55.420
I am so glad
we waited.

28:55.420 --> 28:57.920
So glad.
[ Laughs ]

28:57.920 --> 28:59.500
What the hell, Karev?

28:59.500 --> 29:01.330
Oh, Qadri reported me?

29:01.330 --> 29:04.420
She did her job.
You stabbed a patient?

29:04.420 --> 29:07.880
Look, you said
find a creative solution, right?

29:07.880 --> 29:11.250
I didn't say commit assault
or insurance fraud.

29:11.250 --> 29:12.290
I mean,
if this is your way

29:12.290 --> 29:13.330
of getting out of
being interim chief,

29:13.330 --> 29:14.540
congratulations.

29:14.540 --> 29:16.460
It'll likely get you
out of being a doctor at all.

29:16.460 --> 29:17.710
Look, I'm just
kicking the job's ass

29:17.710 --> 29:19.920
before it kicks mine,
like your mother said.

29:19.920 --> 29:22.880
No, no. You do not get to use
my mother's words against me.

29:22.880 --> 29:23.960
Well, let me
tell you something

29:23.960 --> 29:25.710
my mother used to say --

29:25.710 --> 29:28.210
"Bats! There are bats
everywhere, Alex,

29:28.210 --> 29:30.380
and they know
everybody's phone numbers."

29:30.380 --> 29:32.580
So, how about you let me borrow
your mom for a minute?

29:32.580 --> 29:34.040
[ Faucet running ]

29:36.080 --> 29:38.000
Evelyn: Of course
it was the right thing.

29:38.000 --> 29:39.710
You drug-test her,
and you ground her.

29:39.710 --> 29:41.500
What's the problem?

29:41.500 --> 29:42.580
Well, I just
have no authority.

29:42.580 --> 29:44.170
I-I'm not her mother or --

29:44.170 --> 29:45.920
What are you?
I don't know.

29:45.920 --> 29:49.330
Her friend?
Or her sponsor maybe?

29:49.330 --> 29:51.210
I-I'm trying to be
whatever she needs.

29:51.210 --> 29:53.670
She needs a damn mother,
sounds like.

29:53.670 --> 29:54.960
So, I should push it?

29:54.960 --> 29:57.580
You're building a boat.

29:57.580 --> 29:58.670
A boat?

29:58.670 --> 30:01.120
It's what I used to tell
Owen's dad.

30:01.120 --> 30:02.880
They're gonna
sail away from us, I said.

30:02.880 --> 30:04.380
It's inevitable.

30:04.380 --> 30:07.580
Our job is to
build a boat strong enough

30:07.580 --> 30:09.540
that,
when they decide to,

30:09.540 --> 30:12.580
they can
get back to us safely.

30:12.580 --> 30:14.080
Right.

30:15.790 --> 30:20.040
So, I need to be firm,
use tough wood,

30:20.040 --> 30:21.290
and hammer in
the nails with --

30:21.290 --> 30:23.580
You're not building
an actual boat.

30:23.580 --> 30:26.120
The boat is
your relationship with --

30:26.120 --> 30:27.620
Right.
No. I-I got it.

30:27.620 --> 30:29.080
Thank you.

30:30.790 --> 30:33.290
Let me ask you this.

30:33.290 --> 30:35.250
Are you and Owen
back together?

30:35.250 --> 30:37.880
I can't tell,
and he won't say.

30:37.880 --> 30:39.580
Uh, I don't know.

30:39.580 --> 30:40.750
I think
we're just kind of --

30:40.750 --> 30:43.330
Raising some kids together
or whatever?

30:45.000 --> 30:46.710
Lord.

30:46.710 --> 30:49.000
Do you have an opinion
either way?

30:49.000 --> 30:51.420
Of course I do, dear.

30:51.420 --> 30:53.040
I'm his mother.

30:55.670 --> 30:58.540
♪ Know you're coming
from a bad place ♪

30:58.540 --> 31:02.040
♪♪

31:02.040 --> 31:03.710
Mr. Forrester.

31:03.710 --> 31:05.120
Is she awake?

31:05.120 --> 31:07.040
Uh...

31:07.040 --> 31:09.710
We think that it's time.

31:09.710 --> 31:11.380
Time for what?

31:11.380 --> 31:14.790
Max, son, I'm -- I'm gonna
go check on Mommy, okay?

31:14.790 --> 31:16.250
Okay.

31:16.250 --> 31:17.920
♪♪

31:17.920 --> 31:19.540
♪ For you to feel like
you again ♪

31:19.540 --> 31:22.080
This could be his last chance
to say goodbye.

31:22.080 --> 31:24.330
Please don't.

31:24.330 --> 31:26.670
This is too much for him.

31:26.670 --> 31:28.830
I mean,
Max shouldn't even be here.

31:28.830 --> 31:31.710
Look, I can take him to get
something to eat, if you like.

31:31.710 --> 31:33.330
Would you mind?
Yeah.

31:33.330 --> 31:34.330
♪ And if your spirit needs
a tourniquet ♪

31:34.330 --> 31:37.120
[ Sighs ] Okay.

31:37.120 --> 31:39.170
♪♪

31:39.170 --> 31:42.120
♪ 'Cause if it does,
I can hold you tight enough ♪

31:42.120 --> 31:43.750
Hey, Max.

31:43.750 --> 31:46.500
You hungry? No?

31:46.500 --> 31:48.040
♪ Help you forget 'em
for a minute, love ♪

31:48.040 --> 31:50.080
Do you want to
see something cool?

31:50.080 --> 31:52.500
I haven't left the country
in a while.

31:52.500 --> 31:54.250
Traveled to Europe
after med school,

31:54.250 --> 31:57.000
but I really need
to go to Switzerland.

31:57.000 --> 31:58.420
Yeah, getting to travel's
the best thing

31:58.420 --> 32:00.250
about being married
to work.

32:00.250 --> 32:01.710
It's the trade-off
for all the sex

32:01.710 --> 32:02.750
that work
doesn't give you.

32:02.750 --> 32:03.920
[ Both chuckle ]

32:03.920 --> 32:05.120
Do you travel a lot?

32:05.120 --> 32:07.040
Um, no, but I can.

32:07.040 --> 32:08.210
I got the time
and the resources

32:08.210 --> 32:09.920
to do whatever.

32:09.920 --> 32:12.500
And there's no kids
to worry about, so...

32:12.500 --> 32:13.750
Ah. Actually --

32:13.750 --> 32:15.080
You know, truly, that --

32:15.080 --> 32:18.830
that is the most frustrating
thing about dating --

32:18.830 --> 32:20.500
the single moms.

32:20.500 --> 32:22.080
There's such a need
to speed things up.

32:22.080 --> 32:23.250
It's like, by the end
of the first date,

32:23.250 --> 32:24.960
they're talking marriage.

32:24.960 --> 32:27.460
Kids can make women so...

32:27.460 --> 32:28.620
Desperate?

32:28.620 --> 32:31.330
Well, I don't want
to call it that.

32:31.330 --> 32:32.830
Yeah. You know what?
I do want to call it that.

32:32.830 --> 32:34.710
[ Chuckles ]

32:34.710 --> 32:35.830
What?
What's wrong?

32:35.830 --> 32:37.750
♪ High hope ♪

32:37.750 --> 32:38.960
You have a kid.

32:38.960 --> 32:40.460
I have three.

32:40.460 --> 32:43.670
And while I don't feel like
I'm on any sort of clock,

32:43.670 --> 32:45.420
I also don't feel like

32:45.420 --> 32:47.000
they're holding me back
from anything.

32:47.000 --> 32:48.790
Yeah. I'm -- I'm sorry.
I really didn't mean...

32:48.790 --> 32:51.880
I know.

32:51.880 --> 32:54.170
I said the One Thing,
didn't I?

32:54.170 --> 32:55.250
But this was fun.

32:55.250 --> 32:59.080
♪ I've got a high ♪

32:59.080 --> 33:00.290
Take care.

33:00.290 --> 33:04.620
♪ I've got a high, high, high ♪

33:04.620 --> 33:09.790
♪ I've got a high, high,
high, high hope ♪

33:09.790 --> 33:15.830
♪♪

33:18.170 --> 33:21.330
Whoa.

33:21.330 --> 33:22.880
Are we even allowed
to be up here?

33:22.880 --> 33:25.540
Uh, not really,
but, uh,

33:25.540 --> 33:27.210
that's part of what
makes it cool, right?

33:29.330 --> 33:30.960
Why don't you
come have a seat, pal?

33:38.290 --> 33:41.290
I know
she's not okay.

33:41.290 --> 33:43.710
I can tell.

33:43.710 --> 33:46.420
Why is my dad
lying to me?

33:46.420 --> 33:47.830
I wouldn't say
he's lying, Max.

33:47.830 --> 33:50.710
He's just trying to...

33:50.710 --> 33:52.420
Look,
when I was in college,

33:52.420 --> 33:55.000
my mom went to go visit
my sister in Italy.

33:55.000 --> 33:57.290
And one day, my sister calls me,
and she says,

33:57.290 --> 33:58.380
"You have to come home
right now.

33:58.380 --> 34:00.380
Mom's really sick."

34:00.380 --> 34:05.540
So, I flew home,
and when I got there...

34:05.540 --> 34:09.250
she had died of a stroke.

34:09.250 --> 34:11.250
But the truth is,
she was already dead

34:11.250 --> 34:13.120
before my sister
even called me.

34:13.120 --> 34:15.290
Your sister lied?
Mm-hmm.

34:15.290 --> 34:17.380
Yeah. She did.

34:17.380 --> 34:20.040
And believe me, Max,
I was so mad at her.

34:20.040 --> 34:23.960
But then she said,

34:23.960 --> 34:25.330
"I couldn't
have you find out

34:25.330 --> 34:28.210
without me being there
to hug you."

34:28.210 --> 34:30.620
And then I understood.
So, my dad is lying?

34:30.620 --> 34:32.540
No.
Is my mom gonna die?

34:32.540 --> 34:33.880
No, Max,
I just mean --

34:33.880 --> 34:35.620
Is she dead already?
Max, no.

34:35.620 --> 34:38.210
I just mean it's hard
to face the truth sometimes.

34:38.210 --> 34:39.710
It's scary,
even for doctors.

34:39.710 --> 34:41.080
W-- Max.

34:41.080 --> 34:42.170
Max, wait!

34:42.170 --> 34:44.080
Hey. Max!
[ Elevator bell dings ]

34:44.080 --> 34:45.120
Max, wait!

34:51.380 --> 34:53.080
[ Indistinct conversations ]

34:53.080 --> 34:55.080
Dr. Grey.
You look nice.

34:55.080 --> 34:56.750
Thanks.
I had a meeting.

34:56.750 --> 34:58.710
Hey!
How was your date?

34:58.710 --> 35:00.380
Oh. Oh,
that kind of meeting.

35:00.380 --> 35:01.290
Oh, let's not.

35:01.290 --> 35:02.670
-Please, let's do.
-Yeah.

35:02.670 --> 35:03.670
[ Clipboard thuds ]

35:03.670 --> 35:07.000
-I hate people.
-Oh, thank God.

35:07.000 --> 35:08.380
This man's wife
is dying,

35:08.380 --> 35:09.330
and he's not
gonna tell his kid

35:09.330 --> 35:10.540
until after
she's already dead,

35:10.540 --> 35:14.540
when it's too late
for him to say goodbye.

35:14.540 --> 35:16.750
-You.
-Me?

35:16.750 --> 35:18.710
Yeah, you should
answer this for me.

35:18.710 --> 35:20.750
If you see a disaster coming

35:20.750 --> 35:23.540
and you have to break
patient confidentiality

35:23.540 --> 35:24.880
to prevent it,

35:24.880 --> 35:26.620
don't you do that?

35:26.620 --> 35:30.500
Like, I-I should tell you,
right -- uh, them -- him?

35:30.500 --> 35:32.250
Well, it's an oath.

35:32.250 --> 35:36.330
And as wrong as it feels,
is it your business?

35:36.330 --> 35:37.750
I hate people.

35:38.830 --> 35:41.620
So, how did it go?

35:41.620 --> 35:43.620
Horribly.

35:43.620 --> 35:46.830
I liked him a lot.
We found each other delightful.

35:46.830 --> 35:49.330
And I thought, "Hey,
could it really be this easy?

35:49.330 --> 35:50.670
How is that horrible?

35:50.670 --> 35:52.380
Because then
he said the One Thing --

35:52.380 --> 35:53.460
that he hates kids

35:53.460 --> 35:55.540
and that he finds
single mothers desperate.

35:55.540 --> 35:58.120
Right. Okay.
Next time!

35:58.120 --> 35:59.790
Right. I don't think
there'll be a next time.

35:59.790 --> 36:02.670
Don't! Don't give up!

36:02.670 --> 36:05.460
For what it's worth, it --
it sounds like a great date.

36:05.460 --> 36:07.460
I mean,
if he hadn't said that thing,

36:07.460 --> 36:08.920
you might
have given it a go,

36:08.920 --> 36:11.500
and then he would have probably
tried to hide his feelings

36:11.500 --> 36:14.420
and the truth might not come out
for months or years.

36:14.420 --> 36:17.460
So, I mean, you found out
there are good men out there,

36:17.460 --> 36:20.120
and you dodged
a very slow-moving bullet.

36:20.120 --> 36:24.040
I'd call that
a good use of your time.

36:24.040 --> 36:26.420
Thanks, Herrera.

36:26.420 --> 36:28.380
Woman on P.A.:
Dr. Mahoney to the ER.

36:28.380 --> 36:29.670
Dr. Mahoney to the ER.

36:29.670 --> 36:31.170
[ Sighs ]

36:31.170 --> 36:32.040
Hey.

36:32.040 --> 36:33.460
Hey.
[ Speaks Italian ]

36:33.460 --> 36:35.040
Have you seen a kid,
10 years old?

36:35.040 --> 36:36.830
You've lost a child,
Andrea?

36:36.830 --> 36:39.120
I didn't lose a child.
I'm looking for one.
Okay.

36:39.120 --> 36:41.250
Oh, uh,
did you hear from Papa?

36:41.250 --> 36:43.290
It's, uh -- Just go.

36:43.290 --> 36:44.460
Go find your kid,
yeah?

36:44.460 --> 36:45.790
All right. Okay.
Yeah.

36:45.790 --> 36:47.080
Oh, oh, uh, Carina?

36:47.080 --> 36:48.580
What?

36:48.580 --> 36:50.000
You're
a really good sister.

36:51.960 --> 36:53.460
[ Elevator bell dings ]

36:53.460 --> 36:54.670
[ Sighs ] Max.

36:55.670 --> 36:56.670
Max?

36:56.670 --> 37:02.330
♪♪

37:02.330 --> 37:04.880
Bye-bye, bleb.

37:04.880 --> 37:06.790
Now he'll breathe
without a problem,

37:06.790 --> 37:08.040
and he doesn't have to worry

37:08.040 --> 37:10.380
about the thing bursting
on its own.

37:10.380 --> 37:13.000
Well, I understand
the medicine, Karev.

37:13.000 --> 37:14.210
What I'm not so sure of

37:14.210 --> 37:16.040
is how you plan
to tell his mother

37:16.040 --> 37:18.710
and a medical ethics
committee.

37:18.710 --> 37:21.290
I'll probably tell them about
the time that I stole a car.

37:23.750 --> 37:26.620
[ Sighs ] One night,
my baby sister, Amber,

37:26.620 --> 37:27.920
had the flu.

37:27.920 --> 37:30.880
She spiked a fever of 104.

37:30.880 --> 37:33.750
I was 12, home alone,
didn't know what to do.

37:33.750 --> 37:36.670
So I broke into
the neighbor's house,

37:36.670 --> 37:39.460
stole the car keys,
and took her to the hospital,

37:39.460 --> 37:41.420
where there were people
who would know what to do.

37:41.420 --> 37:43.170
Why didn't you
just call an ambulance?

37:43.170 --> 37:46.120
[ Sighs ] You know how much
an ambulance ride costs?

37:46.120 --> 37:48.710
I think I'll get a pass
from his mom.

37:48.710 --> 37:52.880
And I'm hoping there's no need
to face an ethics committee.

37:52.880 --> 37:54.170
3-0 Vicryl?

37:56.500 --> 37:59.290
-Can't you drive me home?
-Amelia's gonna do it.

37:59.290 --> 38:00.880
How do you
even deal with her?

38:00.880 --> 38:03.880
Well, for one thing,
I don't lie to her.

38:03.880 --> 38:06.830
And, also, I accept her.

38:06.830 --> 38:09.080
I accept that
she will be a little intense,

38:09.080 --> 38:10.920
a little too much
sometimes

38:10.920 --> 38:13.460
because
she cares so much.

38:13.460 --> 38:15.960
She's trying to help you,
and if you let her,

38:15.960 --> 38:18.120
she might stop
driving you so crazy.

38:22.040 --> 38:24.120
Did you
take the drug test?

38:24.120 --> 38:25.380
No.

38:25.380 --> 38:28.710
Well, uh, I will show you
where the bathroom is.

38:28.710 --> 38:29.790
I smoked some weed.

38:31.460 --> 38:32.790
Me and a friend.

38:32.790 --> 38:34.620
It wasn't heroin.
It wasn't pills.

38:34.620 --> 38:36.210
It was just weed.

38:36.210 --> 38:39.880
There's no
"just weed," okay?

38:39.880 --> 38:43.830
Because when a junkie
smokes weed or drinks,

38:43.830 --> 38:46.380
we sometimes forget
to not do heroin.

38:46.380 --> 38:48.540
It triggers cravings,
all of it, Betty.

38:48.540 --> 38:49.670
And you've been
to plenty of meetings,

38:49.670 --> 38:52.580
so I think
you know that already.

38:52.580 --> 38:53.920
Okay?

38:53.920 --> 38:57.250
So...you're grounded.

38:57.250 --> 39:00.170
One month, no friends,
no hanging out after school.

39:00.170 --> 39:01.420
Wait. One month?

39:01.420 --> 39:02.500
Are you crazy?

39:02.500 --> 39:03.920
Amelia --
Shh!
I am building a boat.

39:03.920 --> 39:05.670
One month --
you go to school,

39:05.670 --> 39:07.120
you come home
and go to meetings.

39:07.120 --> 39:09.170
That is it.
Then we'll talk.

39:09.170 --> 39:11.080
Oh, my God.
Okay, yeah, whatever.

39:11.080 --> 39:13.620
You are so lame.
You are both so lame.

39:13.620 --> 39:15.250
I'll be in the car.

39:15.250 --> 39:18.040
[ Exhales heavily ]

39:18.040 --> 39:20.080
We are lame.
We're so lame.

39:20.080 --> 39:21.920
[ Chuckles ]

39:21.920 --> 39:23.750
[ Valerie Broussard's
"Hold On To Me" plays ]
[ Sighs ]

39:23.750 --> 39:26.420
Hi, Julius.
Surgery went well.

39:26.420 --> 39:28.290
We removed the bleb
with no problem,

39:28.290 --> 39:30.710
and you have
two very healthy lungs.

39:30.710 --> 39:32.750
You stab people?

39:32.750 --> 39:35.290
To --
To give them surgery?

39:35.290 --> 39:37.250
Meredith: My mother said,
"Tell the truth."

39:37.250 --> 39:39.920
You needed the surgery,
and you needed it covered.

39:39.920 --> 39:42.000
My mom's gonna go crazy.

39:42.000 --> 39:44.830
♪ But I promise there is a light
at the end of this long ride ♪

39:44.830 --> 39:47.670
No. Crazy happy.

39:47.670 --> 39:50.040
She's been saving for this,
like, forever.

39:50.040 --> 39:51.580
♪ This time I know... ♪

39:51.580 --> 39:53.790
"Just tell the best version
of the truth you can."

39:53.790 --> 39:55.710
Hey, won't you get fired
for this?

39:55.710 --> 39:58.580
Oh, probably not.
I'm the chief.

39:58.580 --> 40:00.290
[ Chuckles ]

40:00.290 --> 40:02.210
♪ 'Cause when you feel like ♪

40:02.210 --> 40:04.580
♪ You've been falling ♪
[ Door opens ]

40:04.580 --> 40:05.540
♪ Hold on to me ♪

40:05.540 --> 40:06.540
I'm sorry.

40:06.540 --> 40:07.750
For calling me
a hooker?

40:07.750 --> 40:09.040
I never called you a...

40:09.040 --> 40:10.250
You suggested
I'd trade sex

40:10.250 --> 40:11.830
for a multimillion-dollar
MRI machine,

40:11.830 --> 40:14.420
which makes me a pretty
high-class hooker, actually.

40:14.420 --> 40:15.420
Link: Tell him
to watch the wound,

40:15.420 --> 40:16.420
and if there's any increase
in redness,

40:16.420 --> 40:17.580
I want to see him
back here -- cool?

40:17.580 --> 40:19.380
Is that...

40:19.380 --> 40:21.750
-That's Link. He's the new --
-Atticus Lincoln?!

40:21.750 --> 40:23.000
Brooke?!

40:23.000 --> 40:24.290
[ Chuckles ] Link?!

40:24.290 --> 40:25.210
[ Laughing ] What?!

40:25.210 --> 40:26.500
Ahh!

40:26.500 --> 40:28.330
[ Laughing ]
Oh, my gosh!

40:28.330 --> 40:30.380
Ahh! You work here?!

40:30.380 --> 40:31.250
I work here!

40:31.250 --> 40:33.000
No way!

40:33.000 --> 40:34.830
Because the truth
is gonna come out sometime.

40:34.830 --> 40:38.960
♪ Life, an ocean ♪

40:38.960 --> 40:41.120
♪ Keeps pulling
your anchor down ♪

40:41.120 --> 40:43.540
He saying his goodbyes?

40:43.540 --> 40:45.000
♪ Deep ♪

40:45.000 --> 40:46.750
His kid still doesn't even know
what's coming.

40:46.750 --> 40:48.000
[ Sighs heavily ]

40:48.000 --> 40:49.080
Keep me posted.

40:49.080 --> 40:50.960
♪ And you can't hear a sound ♪

40:50.960 --> 40:53.290
Hey.

40:53.290 --> 40:56.420
I should have
told him.

40:56.420 --> 40:59.580
I had the chance to tell him,
and I should have.

40:59.580 --> 41:01.710
Nobody wants a surprise
like that.

41:01.710 --> 41:02.880
♪ This time I know
you'll be all right ♪

41:02.880 --> 41:04.420
You deserve a heads-up.

41:04.420 --> 41:08.670
"Surprise.
Your mother's gone."

41:08.670 --> 41:11.960
"Surprise. Your boyfriend
went to go be with the trees."

41:11.960 --> 41:13.710
"Surprise, Amelia."

41:13.710 --> 41:15.170
♪ 'Cause when you feel like
you've been falling ♪

41:15.170 --> 41:16.290
♪ Hold on to me ♪

41:16.290 --> 41:18.380
"Surprise, Amelia,"
what?

41:18.380 --> 41:20.420
And the one thing
you can't do with the truth

41:20.420 --> 41:21.960
is hide from it...

41:21.960 --> 41:24.540
Teddy Altman is pregnant.

41:24.540 --> 41:26.880
It's Owen's baby.

41:26.880 --> 41:29.290
Owen doesn't know,
Amelia doesn't know,

41:29.290 --> 41:31.330
and I just broke
doctor/patient confidentiality

41:31.330 --> 41:33.540
by telling you.

41:33.540 --> 41:35.380
♪ Hold on to me ♪

41:35.380 --> 41:36.880
Max!

41:36.880 --> 41:37.750
♪ Whoa, oh, oh ♪

41:37.750 --> 41:38.880
Have you guys
seen Max?

41:38.880 --> 41:40.290
No. I thought
he was with you.

41:40.290 --> 41:43.460
I lost him, okay?
I-I lost Max.

41:43.460 --> 41:45.380
He ran away,
and I can't find him anywhere.

41:45.380 --> 41:47.580
Max!

41:47.580 --> 41:49.040
...because the truth
is gonna come looking...

41:49.040 --> 41:51.500
♪ I won't let you drown ♪

41:51.500 --> 41:53.960
♪ Hold on to me ♪

41:53.960 --> 41:55.960
...until it finds you.

41:55.960 --> 41:58.000
♪ Hold on to me ♪

41:58.000 --> 41:59.710
[ Siren wails in distance ]

42:10.210 --> 42:18.380
♪♪

42:18.380 --> 42:26.580
♪♪

42:26.580 --> 42:32.580
♪♪
